## 4. Threading Model

### Rule: Zero Tkinter widget access from background threads

Tkinter is not thread-safe. Any widget read or write from a non-main thread is undefined behaviour and causes random freezes or crashes.

ARM enforces this with the **filter snapshot pattern**:

```
Button click (main thread)
    │
    ├─ Read all widget values NOW  ─→  f = _snapshot_filter()  [dict of plain Python values]
    ├─ Read tree rows NOW          ─→  serials = [...]
    │
    └─ threading.Thread(target=worker, args=(serials, f)).start()
                │
                │  Background thread — touches NO Tkinter widgets
                ├─ DB queries using f["pool"], f["from_dt"], etc.
                ├─ HTTP calls
                ├─ self.log(...)          ─→  self.after(0, lambda: ...) back to main
                └─ self._insert_tree_row(...)  ─→  self.after(0, lambda: ...)
```

### Thread lifecycle

| Thread | Trigger | Joins? |
|---|---|---|
| `_search` | Search button | No (daemon) |
| `_reprocess_worker` | Reprocess Selected / Reprocess All buttons | No (daemon) |
| Auto-advance search | `_advance_on_main()` via `self.after()` | No (daemon) |

All threads are `daemon=True` — they are killed automatically when the main window closes without needing explicit join/cleanup.

### Concurrency risk: `self.processed` and `self.result_data`

These two dict/set are written by background threads and read on the main thread (in `view_data` and `export_excel`). In CPython, GIL-protected dict/set operations are atomic for simple get/set/add, so no explicit lock is currently used. If porting to a non-CPython runtime, wrap accesses in a `threading.Lock`.

