#### 6.3.3 Filter snapshot pattern

```python
def _snapshot_filter(self) -> dict:
```

Reads all five filter values from Tkinter widgets and returns them as a plain Python `dict`. Must always be called on the **main thread**. The returned dict is then passed as argument `f` to all background threads — zero widget reads happen inside threads.

**Return value:**

```python
{
    "pool":       str,       # e.g. "MI_POOL_01"
    "sync_queue": str,       # e.g. "SYNC_Q_A"
    "sync_pat":   str,       # e.g. "%SYNC_Q_A%" (LIKE pattern)
    "from_dt":    datetime,  # CET-aware datetime (or None)
    "to_dt":      datetime,  # CET-aware datetime (or None)
}
```

---

#### 6.3.4 Thread launchers

All three launchers run on the main thread. They snapshot state first, then hand it off to a daemon thread.

##### `_thread_search()`

```python
f = self._snapshot_filter()
threading.Thread(target=self._search, args=(f,), daemon=True).start()
```

##### `_thread_reprocess_selected()`

Reads `self.tree.selection()` (main thread only), maps to serial numbers, snapshots filter, then starts `_reprocess_worker` with `advance_queue=False`.

##### `_thread_reprocess_all()`

Reads `self.tree.get_children()` (main thread only), maps to serial numbers, snapshots filter, then starts `_reprocess_worker` with `advance_queue=True`.

Both reprocess launchers guard against empty inputs with `messagebox.showwarning` before starting the thread.

---

#### 6.3.5 Thread-safe UI helpers

All methods below schedule work on the main thread via `self.after(0, callback)` and are safe to call from any thread.

| Method | Signature | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `log` | `(message: str) → None` | Appends `[HH:MM:SS] message\n` to `self.log_text` and scrolls to end |
| `_show_error` | `(title, msg) → None` | Shows `messagebox.showerror` on the main thread |
| `_show_warning` | `(title, msg) → None` | Shows `messagebox.showwarning` on the main thread |
| `_clear_log` | `() → None` | Deletes all content from `self.log_text` |
| `_clear_tree` | `() → None` | Removes all rows from `self.tree` |
| `_insert_tree_row` | `(values: tuple) → None` | Inserts one row into `self.tree` using a default-argument lambda to capture the value correctly |

> **Lambda capture note:** `_insert_tree_row` uses `lambda v=values: ...` (not `lambda: ...`) to capture the current value of `values` at the time of scheduling, preventing the classic Python late-binding closure bug.

