## 15. Known Limitations & Future Improvements

### Current limitations

| Limitation | Detail |
|---|---|
| No concurrent reprocessing | Serials are processed sequentially within a single thread. For large batches, this can be slow. |
| SSL verification disabled | `verify=False` in all API calls suppresses certificate validation warnings. This is a security risk on untrusted networks. |
| No session persistence across login | `self.processed` and `self.result_data` are lost when the user logs out and logs back in. |
| Pool list loaded once at startup | If a new pool is added to the DB after the app opens, it won't appear without restarting. |
| No progress bar | Large batches provide no visual indication of how many items remain. |
| `self.processed` / `self.result_data` not locked | Safe in CPython due to the GIL, but not portable to Jython or other runtimes. |

### Suggested improvements

| Improvement | Description |
|---|---|
| **Parallel reprocessing** | Use `concurrent.futures.ThreadPoolExecutor` to process multiple serials concurrently, bounded by a configurable worker count |
| **Re-enable SSL verification** | Pass the correct CA bundle via `verify="/path/to/ca-bundle.crt"` |
| **Progress bar** | Add a `ttk.Progressbar` that updates per-serial via `self.after()` |
| **Cancel button** | Add a `threading.Event` stop flag that workers check between serials |
| **Retry logic** | On API failure (non-200), retry up to N times with exponential backoff before marking as failed |
| **Persist results** | Save `result_data` to a local SQLite DB so results survive logout/login cycles |
| **Pool list refresh button** | Add a refresh button next to the Pool dropdown to reload without restarting |
| **Row colour update** | After a serial is processed successfully, update its Treeview row tag to `"processed"` (green) in real time |
